\par What Elisabeth and Cynthia had originally proposed was to conduct a roundtable discussion about the relationships between modernist and contemporary poetics, and the idea was to circulate a list of questions some time over the summer for Kathleen, Carla, 
and Lorenzo to respond to in advance of the conference.  One of the first e-mails I received on this after 9-11-01 was from Elisabeth.
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 {Dear Kathleen, Carla, & Lorenzo,
\par 
\par On behalf of Michael, Cynthia & myself, I\rquote m sorry for being out of touch
\par for so long about our upcoming panel at MSA.  At the moment, it all seems
\par surreal & irrelevant, especially here in NYC, where we are all only
\par beginning to absorb the ramifications of this last week.  I am enormously
\par lucky not to have been directly affected, but work remains difficult in
\par many ways.  My e-mail is not functioning at home; long distance calls
\par rarely go through; and a feeling of emergency prevails.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
\par Here in south-central Pennsylvania, I felt a benumbed and uncanny calm for days, even as the ROTC, which is housed in my office building, was more animated and busy than I'd seen before\emdash 
I saw lots of ROTC students carrying guns and military hardware in and out of my building.  A ROTC student in my Intro to Poetry class was more upset than I\rquote d ever seen him, visibly shaking as we discussed (by coincidence that week\emdash 
it was just where the chapters ended up in my intro textbook) Wilfred Owen\emdash \'93the great lie.\'94
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {Elisabeth\rquote s e-mail continued:
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
\par }\pard \ql \li1440\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1440\itap0 {The MSA conference seems to remain as planned.  As to our panel?  Perhaps a
\par broader perspective is in order.  Not just \'93modernism\'94 but our future(s)?
\par Whatever the subjects of our conversation, we hope as much direction as
\par possible comes from the three of you.  Over the next day or so, we will
\par brainstorm some subjects & questions.  We ask that the three of you look
\par back at the original proposal (pasted in below) & use that as a point of
\par departure for a few issues/questions to be sent to me.  Michael & I can
\par then organize the results & send a copy to all of you in preparation for
\par our panel.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs20 
\par }{Kathleen, Carla, Lorenzo, and Cynthia soon followed with responses.  Kathleen wondered about the viability of even doing the MSA conference and questioned the need for more academic presentations in the face of this historical situation.  But Lorenzo
\rquote 
s e-mail touched an especially strong response in me.  He touched on how participating in the MSA might meet a pressing need for community but also serve the need to act in the face of a growing intolerance, a hysterical vertigo of machismo, the lan
guage of \'93enduring freedom,\'94and the drumbeats for \'93eternal justice.\'94  He noted some striking historical parallels between the situation for many radical and minority writers during the early 20}{\super th}{
 century in the wake of the Palmer raids which seemed precisely to the point, especially given our panel\rquote 
s original theme.  To what extent might we think about the notion of modernist innovation as a response to the historical experience of state-sponsored repression in the US and to the Palmer regime, in particular
?  Lorenzo was highlighting a dimension of African American modernism I could not recall having been adequately examined.  The same day that Lorenzo wrote, Carla\rquote 
s response articulated both the sense of emergency so resonant in those first days and a kind 
of immanent narrativity connecting the seemingly disparate moments she related, offering some kind of suturing for what seemed so damaging and fragmented.  Cynthia wrote out of her then current work on Marianne Moore and the need for an ethical poetics.  
I had just read Cynthia\rquote s paper on this topic, and it raised a number of issues I found quite compelling about a commitment to a poetics of moral concern, of conduct.  As Sidney wrote in }{\i Apology for Poetry}{: \'93
The Ethicke and politick consideration, with the end of well dooing and not of well knowing onely.\'94
  How to write after historical disaster, in the face of organized violence of the level of 9-11 (or of the Red Summer, World War I, the Holocaust, the Vietnam War, on & on) in a way that does not reiterate the epistemological shape of violence?  It
\rquote s an old question.
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {Here\rquote s my contribution to this e-mail discussion:
