[w]hat [Marianne Moore and Alice Fulton] call for is a less visually, formally, and thematically stabilized poetry\emdash a poetry that is on the verge or at the edge. . . . Fulton is interested in a poetry open to the fluctuations of }{\i conscious}{, }{
\i mindfulness, openheartedness}{.\'94  She\rquote s interested in the point at which \'93structure is incipient, all threshold, a neither-nor\'94 (4).  Cynthia sees Fulton\rquote s work as expressing a concern with the \'93ethical aspect of the arti
stic practice,\'94 as \'93reconstructive (rather than revolutionary)\'94 (8).  Rather than \'93rupture\'94 as incipient, structure, coherence.  This notion also reminded me of Kathleen\rquote s essay on a \'93local coherence\'94 as a recuperative poetics.

\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {Some of what Cynthia\rquote s paper
 was suggesting about the notion of a coherence that is also on the edge was corroborated for me by a conversation I had with Kathleen in Houston about \'93edges\'94\emdash 
that while they may be viewed as breaks, gashes, wounds, as traces of violence, it is important to consider what\rquote 
s at the edge, who speaks from the edge, the margin, how the edge might be a threshold, a potentiality, a verge.  As Kathleen asked in her essay, \'93Partial local coherence\'94:
