\par On my way to Harrisburg International Airport to catch my flight to Houston on October 12, the traffic along Rt. 581 was backed up for miles\emdash a car had caught fire up ahead (an emergency).  Sitting in traffic, I heard an NPR report on 
the increased interest after 9-11 among anti-terror professionals in the use of \'93Social Network Analysis,\'94
 a largely academic field which combines sociology, statistics, math, and computer science to analyze behavior patterns in social groups.  On the program, an expert in this field said that Social Network Analysis focuses on \'93Isolates\'94
: individuals who tend to act apart from the social group\emdash they tend to be \'93different\'94 and often act alone and against the social group.  It is believed that by identifying 
isolates in terrorist groups, the U.S. could find potential informants and, thus, disrupt a terrorist cell.  Along with isolates, network analysis also tries to identify individuals with \'93centrality\'94\emdash 
those who are well-connected and yet are not the main po
wer of the group.  These individuals may likely have the ability to spread disinformation within the group that need not be scrutinized closely, since such individuals are so well-connected.  Another element of concern was \'93betweenness,\'94
 a characteristic o
f certain individuals within a group who move easily between others and, thus, may act as a conduit or circuit in the social system.  The applicability of Social Network Analysis for anti-terrorist work seems to be its ability to chart connections within 
social groups through \'93pattern recognition\'94
 and exploit those connections so as to disrupt the group from within.  By exploiting the outsiderhood of an isolate, for example, law enforcement might be able to coerce this individual to betray the group.  By ex
ploiting the connectedness of persons with traits of \'93betweennenss\'94 the state could circulate disinformation within the group to undermine it.  
\par }\pard \ql \fi720\li0\ri0\sl480\slmult1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {Besides the eerieness of the jargon used in Social Network Analysis and its \'93big brother\'94
 potential and the uncanny chill it gave me listening about it on my car radio as I sat in a traffic jam, a car on fire up ahead, my flight due to leave in an hour, on Oct. 12, just a month and a day after the attacks, it also occurred to me how this news
 
might relate to my conundrums about modernist and contemporary poetics, about the possibilities for narrativity and paratactic/syntactic disruptiveness.  In some ways this story reveals how such analytical and discursive modes can be seen as inscribed int
o the workings of power.  \'93Disruption\'94 is the goal of the new narrativity of Social Networks Analysis\emdash this field that monitors groups for patterns, that searches out connections, sutures\emdash 
which are also always already points of fissure, potential gaps, potential breaks or ruptures in the system to be exploited and torn open\emdash 
bears out much of the post-structural analysis of hegemonic formation (see Laclau and Mouffe).  Patterns are always about connections while at the same time they are always an arrangement 
of ruptures, however elided or well-concealed.  No system is monolithic, seamless, without fissures.  
\par The outsiderhood so often mythologized in literary cultures is itself the potential partner of power\emdash the very asocial character of the isolate makes the individual more susceptible to carrying out the behests of power\emdash 
although undermining the isolate\rquote s immediate group, this individual serves the needs of another group.
